- Singles‑forward, lyric‑centric presentation: Although the Glen Campbell mastering is described as transparent and warm (a positive), the emphasis on midrange‑centered, lyric‑forward vocals and single‑session sequencing tends toward the “concise, hook‑driven” aesthetic I dislike. I also prefer vocals embedded in a harmonic tapestry rather than front‑and‑center lyric‑forward treatments.
- Less alignment with long‑form audiophile priorities: While the Glen Campbell set preserves dynamics and spatial warmth, it does not deliver the combination of uncompressed audiophile mastering, extended live arrangements and immersive start‑to‑finish flow that are the highest priorities from my self‑description.
Net assessment: Although I stated a general affection for intimate, analog‑warm studio sessions, the live piano recording satisfies the critical technical and musical priorities that matter most to me right now—piano focus, uncompressed/audiophile sound, wide dynamics, extended medleys and an immersive, deliberate album flow—while the Glen Campbell compilation embodies several elements I explicitly avoid (greatest‑hits format and concise singles). For those reasons I select the piano‑centered, uncompressed live recording.

